The '''Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market''' 2016/0280(COD), also known as the '''EU Copyright Directive''', is a controversial proposed [[European Union]] [[Directive (European Union)|directive]] intended to ensure "a well-functioning marketplace for the exploitation of works and other subject-matter... taking into account in particular digital and cross-border uses of protected content".<ref name="EC2016">{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52016PC0593|title= Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market|author=[[European Commission]]|date=14 September 2016}}</ref> It extends existing [[copyright law of the European Union|European Union copyright law]] and is a component of the EU's [[Digital Single Market]] project.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/eu-copyright-legislation |title=The EU copyright legislation |author=European Commission|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref> First introduced by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] on 20{{Nbsp}}June 2018, the directive was approved by the European Parliament on 12{{Nbsp}}September 2018, and is currently passing through formal [[Formal Trilogue meeting|Trilogue]] discussions that are expected to conclude in January 2019. If formalised, each of the EU's member countries would then be required to enact laws to support the directive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/eu-article-13-passed-meme-war|title=The EU has passed Article 13, but Europe's meme war is far from over|last=Volpicelli|first=Gian|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>

The [[European Council]] describe their key goals as protecting press publications, reducing the "value gap" between the profits made by internet platforms and content creators, encouraging "collaboration" between these two groups, and creating [[copyright exceptions]] for [[text and data mining]].<ref name="EUJune252">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|title=Copyright rules for the digital environment: Council agrees its position – Consilium|publisher=Europa (web portal)|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> The directive's specific proposals include giving press publishers direct copyright over use of their publications by internet platforms such as online [[News aggregator|news aggregators]] ([[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market#Article 11|Article 11]]) and requiring websites who primarily host [[User-generated content|content posted by users]] to take "effective and proportionate" measures to prevent unauthorised postings of copyrighted content or be liable for their users' actions ([[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market#Article 13|Article 13]]).

Articles 11 and 13 have attracted widespread criticism from European and American parties. Article 11 has been criticised as a "link tax" which would require websites "to obtain a license before linking to news stories",<ref name="effdeeplinks"/> and Article 13 as a "[[Internet meme|meme]] ban", on the basis that the content-matching technologies employed to meet its requirements cannot identify [[fair dealing]] such as [[parody]].<ref name="BBC2018Meme" /> Supporters of the directive, largely media groups and publishers, reject these arguments and claim that a [[disinformation]] and [[astroturfing]] campaign is being carried out by big internet platforms such as [[Google]].<ref name=":1" /><ref name="mythbuster">{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersright.eu/mythbuster|title=MYTHBUSTER|last=|first=|date=|website=publishersright.eu|publisher=[[European Magazine Media Association]] and others|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukmusic.org/news/uk-music-chief-slams-google-as-corporate-vultures-as-figures-show-googles-3|title=UK Music chief slams Google as “corporate vultures” as figures show Google’s €31m EU lobbying bid|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[UK Music]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-funds-activist-site-that-pushes-its-views-rg2g5cr6t|title=Google funds website that spams for its causes|last=Media&nbsp;Correspondent|first=Matthew Moore|date=2018-08-06|work=The Times|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>

In November 2018 Google began openly campaigning against the proposal, threatening to shut down [[YouTube]] in the EU unless concessions are made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/saveyourinternet/|title=#SaveYourInternet - Article 13|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref>

== History ==
===Background===
The European Union's (EU) first attempt to unify copyrights in light of digital technologies was adopted in 2001 as the [[Copyright Directive|Copyright Directive 2001/29/EC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-01-528_en.htm|title=Commission welcomes adoption of the Directive on copyright in the information society by the Council|author=[[European Commission]]|date=4 July 2018}}</ref> The Directive's major objectives were to harmonise EU legislation with international law (as set by the 1996 [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] treaties), to strengthen intellectual property protection, to reduce conflicts in copyright laws between member states, and to assure adequate remuneration to content producers.<ref name="CESP 2015">{{cite report | url = https://www.ceps.eu/system/files/SR120_0.pdf | title = The Implementation, Application and Effects of the EU Directive on Copyright in the Information Society | authors = Andrea Renda, Felice Simonelli, Giuseppe Mazziotti, Alberto Bolognini and Giacomo Luchetta | publisher = [[Centre for European Policy Studies]] | date = November 2015 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 }}</ref> While some parts of the 2001 Directive were effective, other parts of the directive were not satisfactory for the current digital market long after its implementation. In 2012, the [[European Commission]] (EC) announced that they would be reviewing the 2001 Directive and having stakeholder discussions in light of several issues raised with failed copyright proposals from those in the [[European Commissioner for Internal Market and Services]] position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/battle-on-eu-copyright-law-re-opened-by-commission/|title=Battle on EU copyright law re-opened by Commission|date=5 December 2012|work=POLITICO|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> The EC took public comments from December 2013 through March 2014, and published its first report on the state of the EU copyright law in July 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/internal_market/consultations/2013/copyright-rules/docs/contributions/consultation-report_en.pdf|title=Report on the responses to the Public Consultation on the Review of the EU Copyright Rules|last=Directorate General Internal Market and Services Directorate D – Intellectual property D1|date=July 2014|website=|dead-url=}}</ref>

In 2014, [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] was elected to the [[President of the European Commission|presidency of the European Commission]] and took office in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-27679170 | title = Profile: EU's Jean-Claude Juncker | date =15 July 2014 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[BBC]] }}</ref> In his campaign position, Juncker saw the potential to improve the EU's financial status by harmonising the various digital marketplaces among member nations to create job opportunities and drive a knowledge-based society. Juncker placed [[Andrus Ansip]] as Vice-President for the Digital Single Market within the EC that year, tasked with working with the [[European Commissioner for Digital Economy and Society]] (at the time, [[Günther Oettinger]]) and other sections within the EC to come up with the necessary legislative steps that would be required to implement a Digital Single Market.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-523_en.htm | title = Questions and Answers: The Juncker Commission | date = 10 September 2014 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[European Commission]] }}</ref> Initial plans for the legislative steps and their potential impact were announced by the EC in May 2015. Ansip stated that by the implementation of a Digital Single Market, they could increase the European [[gross domestic product]] by as much as {{€|415{{nbsp}}billion|link=yes}} per year.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/may/06/eu-unveils-plans-digital-single-market-online-firms |title = EU unveils plans to set up digital single market for online firms | first =Ian | last = Traynor | date = 6 May 2015 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | work = [[The Guardian]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1447773803386&uri=CELEX:52015DC0192|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions – A Digital Single Market Strategy for Europe|date=6 May 2015|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|series=COM/2015/0192|dead-url=|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> The [[European Parliament]], following up on a report on the state of European Copyright from MEP [[Julia Reda]] that identified several inadequacies of the 2001 Copyright Directive, affirmed support for the EC's goal of a Digital Single Market as well as supporting an initiative with the EP for similar copyright reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&reference=P8-TA-2015-0273&language=EN&ring=A8-2015-0209|title=European Parliament resolution of 9 July 2015 on the implementation of Directive 2001/29/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 22 May 2001 on the harmonisation of certain aspects of copyright and related rights in the information society (2014/2256(INI))|date=9 July 2015}}</ref> The EC subsequently began working on establishing the legal framework by the end of 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=COM:2015:626:FIN|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions – Towards a modern, more European copyright framework|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|series=COM/2015/0626|archive-date=9 December 2015|dead-url=|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref>

===Legislative process===
The first draft of the proposed Directive from the EC was issued on 14{{Nbsp}}September 2016,<ref>{{cite report | url = https://ec.europa.eu/transparency/regdoc/rep/1/2016/EN/1-2016-593-EN-F1-1.PDF | title = Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on Copyright in the Digital Single Market | date = 14 September 2016 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[European Commission]] }}</ref> Following revisions, the [[Council of the European Union]]'s [[Committee of Permanent Representatives]] (COREPER) approved of the EC's legislative directives on 25 May 2018 and prepared to bring the matter to vote in the EP,<ref name="consilium_europa01">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|title=Proposal for a directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market|last=|first=|date=25 May 2018|website=|page=26|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=|ref=}}</ref> to reach a final text, without the support of Germany, Finland, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Belgium, or Hungary.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=EU Council agrees Copyright Directive position|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/eu-council-agrees-copyright-directive-position/|newspaper=CREATe|date=29 May 2018}}</ref> The [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] finalised their amendments to the directive on 20 June 2018 and put them toward the parliament for negotiation.<ref name="EUJune25">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|title=Copyright rules for the digital environment: Council agrees its position|last=|first=|date=2018-05-25|website=|publisher=[[European Council]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>

[[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]] (MEPs) voted on 5{{Nbsp}}July 2018 not to proceed to the negotiation stage, but instead to reopen the directive for debate in September 2018.<ref name="theguardianeuvote">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|title=YouTube and Facebook escape billions in copyright payouts after EU vote|last=Sweney|first=Mark|last2=Rankin|first2=Jennifer|date=2018-07-05|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref><ref name="rejectjuly-5-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=MEPs reject EU copyright reforms in victory for internet giants|last=Khan|first=Mehreen|date=2018-07-05|website=|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref> There were 318 votes to re-open the debate, 278 to proceed, and 31 abstentions.<ref name=":6">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44712475|title=EU's controversial copyright plan rejected|date=2018-07-05|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/eu-parlament-zu-urheberrecht-umstrittene-reform-ueberraschend-ausgebremst-a-1216741.html |title=EU-Parlament bremst Urheberrechtsreform aus |access-date=2018-07-06 |date=2018-07-05 |last=Böhm |first=Markus |website=[[Der Spiegel]] |language=de}}</ref>

On 12{{Nbsp}}September 2018, an updated position of the parliament was approved with the final vote being 438{{Nbsp}}in favour and 226{{Nbsp}}against,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/12/17849868/eu-internet-copyright-reform-article-11-13-approved|title=EU approves controversial Copyright Directive, including internet ‘link tax’ and ‘upload filter’|date=12 September 2018|last=Vincent|first=James|website=The Verge|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref> meaning that [[Formal Trilogue meeting|trilogue negotiations]] can start between the [[European Commission]], the [[Council of the European Union]] and the [[European Parliament]], with an expected conclusion in early 2019. Should the three groups agree to the final language, then the directive will be sent to governments of the 28 member states to be passed as laws within those countries, with each country formalising certain processes as necessary to meet their existing laws.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/09/european-parliament-approves-copyright-bill-slammed-by-digital-rights-groups/ | title=  What’s in the sweeping copyright bill just passed by the European Parliament | first=  Timothy | last=  Lee | date = 12 September 2018 | accessdate = 12 September 2018 | work = [[Ars Technica]] }}</ref>

== Content ==

=== Article 3 ===

Article 3 proposes a [[Limitations and exceptions to copyright|copyright exception]] for [[text and data mining]] (TDM) for the purposes of scientific research.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=9 June 2018|title=Copyright Reform: Help Us Ensure an Effective TDM Exception! – LIBER|url=https://libereurope.eu/blog/2017/09/25/copyright-reform-help-us-ensure-an-effective-tdm-exception/|newspaper=LIBER|date=25 September 2017}}</ref> The COREPER version has both a mandatory and an optional extension.<ref name ="consilium_europa01"/>

Depending on whether it acknowledges the [[public domain]] status of facts and information, the TDM exception could increase or decrease restrictions compared to the status quo.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=12 June 2018|title=24 organisations urge Rapporteur Axel Voss MEP to strike a more ambitious deal on TDM – European Alliance for Research Excellence|url=http://eare.eu/24-organisations-urge-rapporteur-voss-reach-ambitious-deal-tdm/|newspaper=European Alliance for Research Excellence|date=8 June 2018}}</ref>

=== Article 4 ===

Article 4 proposes a mandatory exception for the use of copyrighted works as part of "digital and cross-border teaching activities". This article, when implemented, would clarify that educational establishments can make non-commercial use of copyrighted works for illustrative purposes.{{cn|date=July 2018}}

There have been worries from the educational sector that the exception proposed in article 4 is too limiting. For example, the sector proposes to broaden the scope of "educational establishments" to include cultural heritage institutions. The most debated part of the article is 4(2), under which the exception would not be available if there are "adequate licenses" available in the market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://education.okfn.org/educators-ask-for-a-better-copyright/|title=Educators ask for a better copyright|date=16 January 2018|work=Open Education Working Group|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>

The COREPER version has changes to reflect the arguments of the education sector, but still includes the debated article 4(2).{{cn|date=July 2018}}

=== Article 11 ===

Article 11 extends the 2001 [[Copyright Directive]] to grant publishers direct copyright over "online use of their press publications by information society service providers".<ref name="EUJune25" /> Under current EU law, publishers instead rely on authors assigning copyright to them and must prove rights ownership for each individual work.<ref name="EPstudy">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=IPOL_STU(2017)596810|title=Strengthening the Position of Press Publishers and Authors and Performers in the Copyright Directive – Think Tank|publisher=European Parliament|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>

The proposal attaches several new conditions to the right, including expiry after one year and exemptions for either copying an "insubstantial" part of a work or for copying it in the course of academic or scientific research.<ref name="EUJune25" /> It is derived from the [[ancillary copyright for press publishers]] which was introduced in Germany in 2013.<ref name="EPstudy" /> Press publishing, "whose purpose is to inform the general public and which are periodically or regularly updated", is distinguished from [[academic publishing|academic]] and [[Scientific literature|scientific]] publishing (Recital 33).<ref name ="consilium_europa01"/>

In their explanatory memorandum, the Council describe existing rights enforcement for online use of press publications as "complex and inefficient" and draw particular attention toward the use of news articles by "news aggregators or media monitoring services" for commercial purposes, and the problems faced by press publishers in licensing their work for such services.<ref name ="consilium_europa01"/> A study commissioned by the European Commission, which analysed the implementation of similar laws in Germany and Spain (with the latter having, notably, resulted in discontinuation of [[Google News]] in that country), found that newspapers actually benefited from the increased exposure (and in turn, ad revenue from traffic) that news aggregation platforms attracted to their online articles, noting that "the German and Spanish cases show that the law can create a right", but that "market forces have valued this right at a zero price".<ref name="ECstudy">{{cite web|url=https://www.asktheeu.org/en/request/4776/response/15356/attach/6/Doc1.pdf|title=Online News Aggregation and Neighbouring Rights for News Publishers|id=Ref. Ares(2017)6256585|year=2017|author=[[European Commission]] contractor}}</ref><ref name="EPstudy" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/11/google-news-spain-to-close-in-response-to-tax-on-story-links|title=Google News Spain to close in response to story links 'tax'|last=Rushe|first=Dominic|date=2014-12-11|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref><ref name=TechCrunch2018>{{cite news |title=European MEPs vote to reopen copyright debate over ‘censorship’ controversy |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/07/05/european-meps-vote-to-reopen-copyright-debate-over-censorship-controversy/ |accessdate=5 July 2018 |work=TechCrunch}}</ref>

The version of the directive voted on by [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] contained explicit exemptions for the act of [[hyperlinking]] and "legitimate private and non-commercial use of press publications by individual users".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://juliareda.eu/2018/06/article-11-13-vote/|title=What’s at stake in the July 5 #SaveYourInternet vote: The text, explained|last=Reda|first=Julia|work=Julia Reda|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>

=== Article 12a ===
Article 12a proposes granting sports event organisers copyright over recordings of their events.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&language=EN&reference=P8-TA-2018-0337|title=Amendments adopted by the European Parliament on 12 September 2018 on the proposal for a directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market|last=|first=|date=12 September 2018|website=|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref>

=== Article 13 ===

Article 13 replaces the "[[Electronic Commerce Directive 2000|mere conduit]]" exemption from copyright infringement from for-profit "[[User-generated content|online content sharing service]] providers" with a new, conditional exemption to liability. These conditions are the implementation of "effective and proportionate measures" to "prevent the availability of specific [unlicensed] works identified by rightsholders", acting "expeditiously" to remove them, and demonstrating that "best efforts" have been made to "[[Notice and stay down|prevent their future availability]]". The article also extends any licenses granted to content hosts to their users, as long as those users are not acting "on a commercial basis".<ref name="consilium_europa01" />

The article directs member states to consider the size of the provider, the amount of content uploaded, and the effectiveness of the measures imposed "in light of technological developments". It also mandates an appeals process,<ref name="consilium_europa01" /> and requires content hosts to share "information on the use of content" with its owners, the lack of which has been a point of contention in the past.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/technology/internet/03youtube.html|title=Royalty Dispute Stops Music Videos in Germany|last=O’Brien|first=Kevin J.|date=|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref>

Article 13 has faced widespread criticism over the possibility that it could create a [[chilling effect]] on online expression. Although the article requires only "best efforts" from providers, it is widely accepted by critics and proponents alike that in order to meet the requirement of preventing future availability, larger companies would need to implement content matching technology similar to [[YouTube]]'s [[Content ID (algorithm)|Content ID]] system.<ref name=":7" /><ref name="BBC2018Meme">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44546620|title='Disastrous' copyright bill vote approved|last=|first=|date=20 June 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Critics emphasise the issue of [[False positives and false negatives|false positives]] within such systems, and their inability to account for copyright limitations such as [[fair dealing]] (leading, they allege, to a "[[Internet meme|meme]] ban").<ref name="CNET2018June22">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/article-13-europes-hotly-debated-eu-copyright-law-explained/|title=Everything you need to know about Europe's new meme-ending war|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=1 July 2018|publisher=CNET}}</ref> Supporters and third parties point out that YouTube has used Content ID for a decade and yet remains a successful host for content of all kinds.<ref name=":7" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://torrentfreak.com/censorship-machines-are-destroying-the-internet-as-we-speak-180624/|title=Censorship Machines are 'Destroying The Internet' As We Speak?|last=|first=|date=2018-06-24|work=TorrentFreak|access-date=2018-07-23|language=en-US}}</ref> Yet YouTube CEO expressed concerns the new legislation could shut down the ability of millions of people to upload to YouTube.<ref name="YouTubeCreatorBlog">{{Cite news|url=https://youtube-creators.googleblog.com/2018/10/a-final-update-on-our-priorities-for.html|title=A Final Update on Our Priorities for 2018|last=|first=|date=2018-10-22|work=YouTube Creator Blog|access-date=2018-12-01|language=en-US}}</ref>

Other claims from critics include suggestions that all content providers will be forced to use expensive content filters, that only major U.S. technology firms had sufficient resources to develop such systems,<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/eu/2018/06/19/the-eus-disastrous-copyright-reform-explained/|title=The EU's disastrous Copyright Reform, explained by its lovers and haters|last=Maack|first=Már Másson|date=19 June 2018|work=The Next Web|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> and that outsourcing the task has privacy implications.<ref name="Rom20182">{{cite journal|last1=Romero-Moreno|first1=Felipe|date=29 May 2018|title=‘Notice and staydown’ and social media: amending Article 13 of the Proposed Directive on Copyright|journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology|pages=1–24|doi=10.1080/13600869.2018.1475906}}</ref>

==== Coverage ====
Article 13's provisions target commercial web hosts which "store and give the public access to a large amount of works or other subject-matter uploaded by its users which [they] organise and promote for profit-making purposes". The proposal makes explicit that this does not include private [[cloud storage]] services, non-profit encyclopedias (such as [[Wikipedia]]), non-profit educational or scientific repositories, nor a variety of other cases.<ref name="consilium_europa01" />

The article's provisions do not apply to all commercial content hosts equally. The proposal explains that "[small and micro enterprises] should only be expected to expeditiously remove specific unauthorised works and other subject matter upon notification by {{Sic|rightholders}}", and that "different measures may be appropriate and proportionate per type of content" <ref name="consilium_europa01" />.  "Small" and "micro" are defined in Title I of the Annex to Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC; {{As of|2018|June}}, this covers businesses with less than 50{{Nbsp}}employees and less than 10{{Nbsp}}million on their annual turnover or annual balance sheet.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2003-05-20|title=Commission Recommendation of 6 May 2003 concerning the definition of micro, small and medium-sized enterprises (Text with EEA relevance) (notified under document number C(2003) 1422)|url=http://data.europa.eu/eli/reco/2003/361/oj/eng|language=en}}</ref>

=== Article 13b ===
Article 13b requires websites which "automatically reproduce or refer to significant amounts of copyright-protected visual works" to "conclude fair and balanced licensing agreements with any requesting rightholders".<ref name=":10" />

=== Article 15 ===

Article 15 aims to allow authors to increase their remuneration in some cases where it is disproportionately low. The proposed articles 14–16, while weaker than systems existing in many member states, would improve the bargaining position of authors and performers.<ref name=EPstudy/>

Associations of authors had proposed a "rights reversion mechanism" which would allow cancelling a [[copyright transfer agreement]] proven to be disadvantageous.<ref name="basca01" >{{cite web |title=Music creators call for EU-wide rights reversion mechanism |url=https://basca.org.uk/2017/10/19/music-creators-call-eu-wide-rights-reversion-mechanism/|website=BASCA|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20170811-ALCS-and-SoA-Briefing-note-on-DSM-directive-and-Juri-amendments.pdf|title=Our Views on the European Commission's Draft Legislation to Modernise the European Copyright Framework and Proposed Amendments|date=August 2017}}</ref>

=== Other articles ===

Other passages of the proposal attempt to clarify the legal status of certain common activities by libraries and of [[orphan works]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=European Parliament votes to improve access to digitised cultural heritage |url=https://pro.europeana.eu/post/european-parliament-votes-to-improve-access-to-digitsed-cultural-heritage|website=Europeana}}</ref>

The amendments approved by some [[European Parliament]] committees would address issues with the [[public domain]] and [[freedom of panorama]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/information_society/newsroom/image/document/2016-37/synopsis_report_-_panorama_exception_-_final_17049.pdf|title=Synopsis report on the 'panorama exception'|website=|dead-url=}}</ref>

==Positions==

===Support===
The directive is supported by publishers,<ref name=enpa/> major music labels, mainstream newspapers, and some artists.<ref name="infosurhoy">{{Cite web|url=http://infosurhoy.com/cocoon/saii/xhtml/en_GB/science/science-eu-copyright-war-a-shame-says-big-tech-lobby-report/|title=Science: EU copyright war ‘a shame’, says big tech lobby [Report]|website=infosurhoy.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref> A campaign organised by the [[European Grouping of Societies of Authors and Composers]] collected over 32,000{{Nbsp}}signatures from creators including [[David Guetta]], [[Ennio Morricone]], [[Jean-Michel Jarre]], and the band [[Air (band)|Air]].<ref name="Indus2018">{{cite news|url=https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/david-guetta-and-all-three-major-labels-are-among-industry-giants-pushing-for-copyright-reform/|title=David Guetta and all three major labels are among industry giants pushing for copyright reform {{!}} TIO|work=''theindustryobserver.com.au''|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Other supporters include musicians [[Paul McCartney]] and [[James Blunt]],<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-mccartney-james-blunt-back-new-european-copyright-law-1124974|title=Paul McCartney, James Blunt Back New European Copyright Law|last=|first=|date=4 July 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en}}</ref> author [[Philip Pullman]] (as head of the [[Society of Authors]]),<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20161205-Submission-to-IPO-on-DSM-directive-dec-2016.pdf|title=The Society of Authors’ Response to the Intellectual Property Office’s Calls for Views on the European Commission’s Draft Legislation to Modernise the European Copyright Framework|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Society of Authors]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name="theverge 11sett 2018">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/11/17845394/eu-copyright-directive-reform-date-vote-article-11-13|title=This is what at stake with the EU’s latest copyright reform|last=Vincent|first=James|date=2018-09-11| access-date= 2018-09-12| work= [[The Verge]]| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911182621/https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/11/17845394/eu-copyright-directive-reform-date-vote-article-11-13 | archive-date=Sep 11, 2018 | deadurl =no}}</ref> the [[Independent Music Companies Association]],<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://impalamusic.org/content/copyright-say-no-scaremongering-and-yes-creators-getting-paid|title=Copyright: say NO to scaremongering and YES to creators getting paid|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Independent Music Companies Association]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref> and German publisher [[Axel Springer SE|Axel Springer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/tensions-heighten-ahead-crunch-eu-copyright-reform-vote|title=Tensions heighten ahead of crunch EU copyright reform vote|website=www.theparliamentmagazine.eu|language=en|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>

Support in the European Parliament is led by the directive's [[rapporteur]], [[Axel Voss]], a member of the European Parliament for Germany and a member of the [[European People's Party group]], another proponent of the directive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eppgroup.eu/news/Axel-Voss-appointed-new-Rapporteur-for-Copyright-Directive|title=Axel Voss appointed new Rapporteur for Copyright Directive|last=|first=|date=2017-06-15|work=eppgroup.eu|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en}}</ref> Political supporters at a national level include the United Kingdom [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-industry-is-totally-united-on-this-issue-uk-music-leads-copyright-delegation-to-brussels/072965|title='The industry is totally united on this issue': UK Music leads copyright delegation to Brussels|access-date=2018-07-23|language=en}}</ref> Voss rejects critics' arguments against the directive, and in particular describes talk of censorship as "unjustified, excessive, objectively wrong and dishonest". He points out that content filtering technology has been in use on [[YouTube]] for a decade without having ever sparked an "anti-censorship campaign",<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axel-voss-europa.de/2018/06/18/stellungnahme-zur-reform-des-urheberrechts/|title=Europäisches Urheberrecht|last=Voss|first=Axel|date=2018-06-18|website=www.axel-voss-europa.de|language=de-DE|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref> and accuses "big [internet] platforms" of mounting a "fake news campaign".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://multimedia.europarl.europa.eu/en/copyright-directive-statement-by-axel-voss-eppde-rapporteur-_I158298-V_v|title=Copyright directive: statement by Axel VOSS (EPP,DE), rapporteur|last=|first=|date=2018-07-02|website=|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|member of Parliament of the United Kingdom]] and the deputy leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], said, "we have got to secure for the workers... the full fruits of their industry. Google are trying to prevent that from happening".<ref name=":8" />

Publishing trade bodies similarly claim that a "bad-faith" "misleading campaign", also called a "[[disinformation]] campaign", is being carried out. They specifically name Wikipedia and [[Google]] as orchestrators,<ref name=enpa/><ref name=":1" /><ref name="mythbuster">{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersright.eu/mythbuster|title=MYTHBUSTER|last=|first=|date=|website=publishersright.eu|publisher=[[European Magazine Media Association]] and others|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukmusic.org/news/uk-music-chief-slams-google-as-corporate-vultures-as-figures-show-googles-3|title=UK Music chief slams Google as “corporate vultures” as figures show Google’s €31m EU lobbying bid|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[UK Music]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/07/05/eu_copyright_vote/|title=European Parliament balks at copyright law reform vote|last=|first=|date=2018-07-05|work=The Register|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en}}</ref> claiming that Wikipedia and other platforms engaged in "{{Sic|inacceptable}} misleading campaigns ... to influence MEPs" and pointing out that Google spent {{€|4.5&nbsp;million}} lobbying in Europe during 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/transparencyregister/public/consultation/displaylobbyist.do?id=03181945560-59 |title=Transparency Register: Google |website=[[Lobby register#European Union|EU Transparency Register]] |access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> is among the sponsors of the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], another leading opponent,<ref name=Reg2018>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/06/20/eu_copyright_reform_article_11_13/|title=JURI's out, Euro copyright votes in: Whoa, did the EU just 'break the internet'?|last=|first=|date=20 June 2018|work=[[The Register]]|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en}}{{better source needed|date=July 2018}}</ref> and was seen asking its partners to lobby against the reform.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a8031d7a-78a0-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=Google criticised for push against EU copyright reform|last=|first=|date=26 June 2018|website=|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref> The publishers argue that licensed content providers such as [[Spotify]] and [[Netflix]] are also negatively affected by the current copyright regime, which they say benefits user-driven platforms such as [[YouTube]] (owned by Google) and [[Facebook]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://makeinternetfair.eu/en/node/18|title=About the transfer of value / value gap|last=|first=|date=|website=makeinternetfair.eu|publisher=[[European Grouping of Societies of Authors and Composers]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=":9" /> They claim reports of [[Spambot|spambots]] flooding MEPs with so many anti-copyright emails that they can no longer carry out their work.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":9" />

Newspapers in open support of the directive pejoratively label some of those opposed as "the largest, richest corporate entities in the world". In an editorial, the Financial Times stated that "YouTube controls 60{{Nbsp}}per cent of all streaming audio business, but pays only 11{{Nbsp}}per cent of the revenues that artists receive".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/20a8d1e0-810a-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=The case for reforming the rules of copyright|last=|first=|date=2018-07-06|website=|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> Others newspapers focus on Article 11, arguing that the reform is a battle between European media pluralism and monopolistic foreign internet giants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.humanite.fr/medias-defendre-le-pluralisme-en-europe-contre-les-geants-du-net-657096|title=Médias. Défendre le pluralisme en Europe contre les géants du Net !|date=2018-06-20|work=L'Humanité|access-date=2018-07-06|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2018/06/18/l-europe-doit-defendre-les-medias-contre-la-loi-des-gafa_1660125|title=L’Europe doit défendre les médias contre la&nbsp;loi des&nbsp;Gafa|work=Libération.fr|access-date=2018-07-06|language=fr}}</ref> In general, there is agreement among mainstream press sources that internet platforms are lobbying against the bill to support their financial interests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|title=YouTube and Facebook escape billions in copyright payouts after EU vote|last=Sweney|first=Mark|last2=Rankin|first2=Jennifer|date=2018-07-05|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-07-05}}<br/>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=MEPs reject EU copyright reforms in victory for internet giants|last=Khan|first=Mehreen|date=2018-07-05|website=|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-05}}<br/>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-searches-for-way-round-eu-copyright-dmrjrgpx2|title=Google searches for way round EU copyright|last=Duke|first=Simon|date=2018-07-01|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}<br/>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-companies-win-reprieve-as-eu-parliament-delays-copyright-law-1530787465|title=Tech Companies Win Reprieve as EU Parliament Delays Copyright Law|last=Schechner|first=Sam|date=2018-07-05|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}<br/>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-06/tech-giants-win-against-media-companies-in-eu-copyright-battle|title=Tech Giants Are Stronger Than Paul McCartney|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>

A group of nine major European press publishers including [[Agence France-Presse]], the [[Press Association]], and the [[European Alliance of News Agencies]] issued a letter strongly supporting the proposal, describing it as "key for the media industry, the consumer’s future access to news, and ultimately a healthy democracy". In the letter, they cite existing state support for struggling news media and argue that it should instead be provided by the "internet giants" which have been "siphoning off" advertising revenue.<ref name="9agencies">{{Cite web|url=https://images.derstandard.at/2017/12/14/brief.pdf|title=Letter by 9 news agencies|last=|first=|date=2017-12-14|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

===Opposition===
[[File:Italian Wikipedia blocked.png|thumb|upright=1.4|The banner block on Italian Wikipedia. Other blocked Wikipedias had analogous messages]]{{Disputed section|Opposition|date=August 2018}}[[File:English Wikipedia EU copyright banner.png|thumb|upright=1.4|The banner on the English Wikipedia seen from a German IP address]]
Articles 11 and 13 of the directive have faced widespread criticism.<ref name="auto">{{Cite journal|last=Stalla-Bourdillon|first=Sophie|last2=Rosati|first2=Eleonora|last3=Turk|first3=Karmen|last4=Angelopoulos|first4=Christina|last5=Kuczerawy|first5=Aleksandra|last6=Peguera|first6=Miquel|last7=Husovec|first7=Martin|date=24 November 2016|title=A Brief Exegesis of the Proposed Copyright Directive|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=2875296|location=Rochester, NY}}</ref><ref name="auto1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/06/eus-copyright-proposal-extremely-bad-news-everyone-even-especially-wikipedia|title=The EU's Copyright Proposal is Extremely Bad News for Everyone, Even (Especially!) Wikipedia|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|date=7 June 2018|access-date=9 June 2018|publisher=Electronic Frontier Foundation}}</ref> They are opposed by more than 200 academics from over 25 research centres, authors, journalists,<ref name=Create20180629/> publishers,<ref name="auto2">{{cite web|url=http://mediapublishers.eu/2017/12/27/small-publishers-take-neighbouring-right-out-of-eu-copyright-reform/|title=Our Op-ed as published in EurActiv: Small publishers: Take ‘neighbouring right’ out of EU copyright reform|website=mediapublishers.eu|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref><ref name="linktaxcb">{{Cite web|url=http://copybuzz.com/copyright/link-tax-editors-story/|title=The Link Tax: An Editor’s story – Copybuzz|website=''copybuzz.com''|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> law scholars,<ref name="auto3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/policy-responses/eu-copyright-reform/|title=EU Copyright Reform|date=22 February 2017|work=CREATe|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref name="auto4">{{Cite web|url=https://peepbeep.files.wordpress.com/2016/10/30-september-2016-openlettercommission-w-s1.pdf|title=Open letter by 40 scholars to the European Commission|date=30 October 2016|website=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref name="auto5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ivir.nl/academics-against-press-publishers-right/|title=Letter by 169 academics|website=|dead-url=}}</ref> Internet experts,<ref name="auto6">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/06/internet-luminaries-ring-alarm-eu-copyright-filtering-proposal|title=70+ Internet Luminaries Ring the Alarm on EU Copyright Filtering Proposal|last=Malcolm|first=Danny O&#039;Brien and Jeremy|date=11 June 2018|access-date=12 June 2018|publisher=Electronic Frontier Foundation}}</ref> cultural institutions,<ref name="create">{{Cite web|url=http://www.create.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/OpenLetter_EU_Copyright_Reform_22_02_2017.pdf|title=Copyright Reform: Open Letter from European Research Centres|date=22 February 2017|website=|dead-url=}}</ref> users, civil rights organisations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leistungsschutzrecht.info/sites/default/files/assets/dokumente/aktuelles/openletter-axelvoss-deletearticle11-english.pdf|title=Letter by 145 civil society organisations|website=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref name="auto7">{{cite web|url=https://www.liberties.eu/en/news/delete-article-thirteen-open-letter/13194|title=Article 13 Open letter – Monitoring and Filtering of Internet Content is Unacceptable|last1=Platform|first1=European Liberties|accessdate=14 June 2018}} (An open letter by Liberties, EDRi, 57 human rights and digital rights organisations).</ref> lawmakers<ref name="auto9">{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalagendaintergroup.eu/more-than-a-hundred-meps-oppose-new-publishers-right/|title=More than a hundred MEPs oppose new publishers right – DAI|website=digitalagendaintergroup.eu|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> and EU studies.<ref name=EPstudy/> Creators are divided, with artists of different opinions either supporting or opposing the directive.<ref name="infosurhoy"/>

Of the European member states, observers believed that Germany, Finland, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Belgium and Hungary had voiced opposition to the directive as introduced in May 2018 with the language for Articles 11 and 13, though the votes themselves are not part of public record. Under European law, a proposal can be blocked by the minority if this minority includes 13 member states or represents more than 35% of the EU's population; the opposing states in May 2018 only amounted to about 25% of the population and thus could not block the Directive. Since then, Italy has issued its statements critical of Articles 11 and 13; Italy's 11% of the EU's population would be sufficient to block any proposal should such a vote happen.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/10/italy-steps-defend-eu-internet-users-against-copyright-filters-who-will-be-next | title = Italy Steps Up To Defend EU Internet Users Against Copyright Filters – Who Will Be Next? | first=  Danny | last = O'Brein | date = 23 October 2018| accessdate = 23 October 2018 | work = [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] }}</ref>

[[Google]], the owner of video-sharing website, [[YouTube]], has opposed the directive since its first inception in 2016, when they argued that the proposals would "turn the internet into a place where everything uploaded to the web must be cleared by lawyers".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.google/outreach-initiatives/public-policy/european-copyright-theres-better-way/|title=European copyright: there's a better way|date=2016-09-14|work=Google|access-date=2018-07-10|language=en}}</ref> In 2018 the company encouraged news publishers in its [[Digital News Initiative]], members of which are eligible for grants from a €150m fund, to lobby MEPs on the proposals.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a8031d7a-78a0-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=Google criticised for push against EU copyright reform|last=|first=|date=26 June 2018|website=|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref> YouTube's chief executive officer, [[Susan Wojcicki]], urged content creators on the platform to take action to oppose the legislation, as it "poses a threat to both [their] livelihood and [their] ability to share [their] voice with the world", and stressing that their [[ContentID]] system was intended to help assure fair management and payments for copyright holders already without government intervention.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/22/youtube-susan-wojcicki-creators-protest-eu-article-13-copyright-law.html | title = YouTube CEO urges YouTube creators to protest European copyright law | first = Julianne| last = D'onfo | date = 22 October 2018 | accessdate = 23 October 2018 | work = [[CNBC]] }}</ref> Wojcicki later wrote that any company implementing the necessary protocols to meet the directive would be a significant financial burden, and for a company the scale of YouTube, "the potential liabilities could be so large that no company could take on such a financial risk".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/12/18087250/youtube-ceo-copyright-directive-article-13-european-union | title = YouTube CEO calls EU’s proposed copyright regulation financially impossible | first = Julie | last= Alexander | date = 12 November 2018 | accessdate = 12 November 2018 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>

[[Facebook]] is also opposed, arguing that the proposal "could have serious, unintended consequences for an open and creative internet".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/european-parliament-votes-against-publishers-right-copyright-law-changes-as-facebook-warns-of-unintended-consequences/|title=European Parliament votes against ‘publisher’s right’ copyright law changes as Facebook warns of ‘unintended consequences’|last=|first=|date=2018-07-05|website=|publisher=Press Gazette|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref>

Campaigners criticise Article 11 as a "[[link tax]]" which would require website publishers "to obtain a license before linking to news stories",<ref name="effdeeplinks">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/06/crucial-next-few-days-eus-copyright-filter-and-link-tax-battle|title=The Crucial Next Few Days In the EU's Copyright Filter and Link Tax Battle|last=O&#039;Brien|first=Danny|date=29 June 2018|work=Electronic Frontier Foundation|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en}}</ref> and Article 13 as a "[[Internet meme|meme]] ban", on the basis that the content-matching technologies employed to meet its requirements cannot identify [[fair dealing]] such as [[parody]].<ref name="BBC2018Meme" /> 

Other campaigners, like the [[Copyright for Creativity]] coalition, claim the duration of copyright is too long, the proposals are outdated, create no harmonisation and a dysfunctional implementation and enforcement of the rules.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://copyright4creativity.eu/2015/01/19/c4ccopyrightmanifesto/ |title=The Copyright Manifesto |publisher=Consensus Optimus, Nicholai Hart Ashton Hart, France |access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref>

Academic criticism has instead emphasised concern about the effectiveness of Article 11's impact on the readership of online publication and of Article 13's obligations on service providers that will "benefit big players".<ref name="Create20180629" /> Individuals who have publicly opposed the law include comedian [[Stephen Fry]]; author [[Neil Gaiman]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/pro/paul-mccartney-joins-celeb-lobbying-european-parliament-over-copyright-reform-vote/|title=Paul McCartney joins crowded fight over online rules|last=|first=|date=4 July 2018|website=|publisher=[[Politico]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> [[Tim Berners-Lee]], creator of the [[World Wide Web]]; [[Vint Cerf]], co-inventor of the [[Internet protocol suite]]; and [[Jimmy Wales]], co-founder of Wikipedia; who raise concerns regarding the costs and effectiveness of upload filters and the negative effects on [[free speech]] online.<ref name="BBC2018">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44482381|title=Protests over Brussels copyright reform|date=15 June 2018|work=''BBC News''|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] and [[Reporters Without Borders]] were among signatories of an open letter opposing article 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://copybuzz.com/copyright/50-human-rights-media-freedom-ngos-ask-eu-delete-censorship-filter-stop-madness/|title=Over 50 Human Rights & Media Freedom NGOs ask EU to Delete Censorship Filter & to Stop © Madness – Copybuzz|website=copybuzz.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition|SPARC Europe]] called for the removal of Article 11, arguing that it would "make the last two decades of news less accessible to researchers and the public, leading to a distortion of the public's knowledge and memory of past events", and if extended to academic publishing, would "in effect ask readers to pay publishers for access to works for which authors, institutions or research funders had already paid publishers to make freely accessible to all under '[[open access]]' terms".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sparceurope.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/CopyrightReformBrief.pdf|title="Copyright in the Digital Single Market" briefing|publisher=SPARC Europe|dead-url=|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref name="Create20180629">{{Cite web|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Academic_Statement_Copyright_Directive_29_06_2018.pdf|title=Copyright Reform: Open Letter from European Research Centres|last=|first=|date=29 June 2018|website=|work=CREATe|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref>

A [[Change.org]] petition has gathered more than 1,033,000{{Nbsp}}signatures {{As of|2018|October|16|lc=y}}.<ref name="CNET2018June22" /><ref name=TechCrunch2018/> A few days before the parliamentary vote, Wikipedia started a campaign against the directive.<ref name=enpa>{{cite web | url=http://enpa.eu/news/enpa-reacts-wikipedia-hostile-campaign-against-copyright | title=ENPA reacts to Wikipedia hostile campaign against Copyright | publisher=[[European Newspaper Publishers' Association]] | date=3 July 2018 | access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref>

Widely critical accounts of the proposal have been published by major newspapers in Austria,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://derstandard.at/2000081976547/Heftige-Kritik-an-EU-Plaenen-Sterben-Internet-Memes-in-Europa|title=EU-Pläne für Uploadfilter könnten Todesstoß für Memes bedeuten – derStandard.at|website=DER STANDARD|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> France,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=Un projet de loi européen pourrait menacer les mèmes sur Internet|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/2018/06/08/32001-20180608ARTFIG00290-un-projet-de-loi-europeen-pourrait-menacer-les-memes-sur-internet.php|newspaper=FIGARO|date=8 June 2018}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/upload-filter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-schroedingers-internet-a-1213496.html|title=Upload-Filter: Liebe Leserin, lieber Leser,|last=Beuth|first=Patrick|date=18 June 2018|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/newsticker/dpa_nt/infoline_nt/netzwelt/article177859184/EU-Ausschuss-stimmt-fuer-Leistungsschutz-und-Uploadfilter.html|title=EU-Ausschuss stimmt für Leistungsschutz und Uploadfilter|last=WELT|date=20 June 2018|work=DIE WELT|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/eu-s-attempt-at-internet-copyright-reform-is-a-ridiculous-own-goal-1.3538030|title=EU's attempt at internet copyright reform is a ridiculous own goal|work=The Irish Times|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2018/06/20/economia/ombre-pi-che-luci-della-riforma-europea-del-copyright-ZqzmbTAGxPIxUJga2Ac1rJ/pagina.html|title=Ombre (più che luci) della riforma europea del copyright|work=La Stampa|access-date=22 June 2018|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2018-06-20/europa-stretta-copyright-arriva-tassa-link-e-meme-rischio-171942.shtml?uuid=AE6SSf9E|title=Europa, stretta sul copyright: arriva la tassa sui link (e meme a rischio)|work=Il Sole 24 ORE|access-date=22 June 2018|language=it}}</ref> Poland,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tokfm.pl/Tokfm/7,130517,23572195,cenzura-internetu-i-podatek-od-linkowania-nowa-dyrektywa.html|title=Będzie cenzura internetu? Ekspertka: To może uderzyć nawet w przeglądy prasy i portale typu Wykop|work=tokfm|access-date=22 June 2018|language=pl-PL}}</ref> Spain,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/03/24/inenglish/1490355715_551697.html|title=Editorial {{!}} A digital agreement|last=País|first=El|date=24 March 2017|work=El País|access-date=22 June 2018|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> and Slovakia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tech.sme.sk/c/20849608/bruselska-smernica-moze-uskodit-otvorenemu-a-slobodnemu-internetu.html|title=Bruselská smernica môže uškodiť otvorenému a slobodnému internetu|last=a.s.|first=Petit Press|work=tech.sme.sk|access-date=22 June 2018|language=sk}}</ref>

145{{Nbsp}}organisations from the areas of human and digital rights, media freedom, publishing, libraries, educational institutions, software developers, and [[Internet service provider]]s signed a letter opposing the proposed legislation on 26 April 2018.<ref name="Index2018">{{cite web|url=https://www.indexoncensorship.org/2018/04/digital-single-market-nightmare/|title=Directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market 'destined to become a nightmare'|website=Index on Censorship|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Some of those opposed include the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], [[Creative Commons]], [[European Digital Rights]],<ref name=Index2018/> the [[Max Planck Society]],<ref name=CNET2018June22/> [[GitHub]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2018/09/11/developers-developers-develope-3.html|title=What developers need to do to save the internet from the EU's looming copyright disaster|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|date=2018-09-11|website=[[Boing Boing]]|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref> various [[Wikimedia]] chapters,<ref name=Index2018/> and the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] (the parent organisation of [[Wikipedia]]).<ref name="WikimediaFoundation">{{cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2018/06/29/eu-copyright-proposal-will-hurt-web-wikipedia/|title=How the EU copyright proposal will hurt the web and Wikipedia|last=Hershenov|first=Eileen|date=29 June 2018|website=''wikimedia.org''|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref> The [[Italian Wikipedia]],<ref name="ItalyWikipedia">{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=3 July 2018|title=Italy Wikipedia shuts down in protest at EU copyright law|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44696302|dead-url=no|department=World News (Europe)|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729060650/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44696302|archive-date=29 July 2018|access-date=29 July 2018}}</ref><ref name="PagesShutDown">{{Cite news|last=Farrell|first=James|date=4 July 2018|title=Italian, Spanish and Polish Wikipedia pages shut down ahead of controversial copyright law|url=https://siliconangle.com/blog/2018/07/04/italian-spanish-polish-wikipedia-pages-shut-down-ahead-controversial-copyright-law/|dead-url=no|department=Blog|work=[[Silicon Angle]]|publisher=Silicon Angle Media|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729062249/https://siliconangle.com/blog/2018/07/04/italian-spanish-polish-wikipedia-pages-shut-down-ahead-controversial-copyright-law/|archive-date=29 July 2018|access-date=29 July 2018}}</ref><ref name="PolishWikipedia">{{Cite news|author=pg/st<!--No other author information availble.-->|date=4 July 2018|title=Polish Wikipedia shuts down in protest at EU copyright law|url=https://polandinenglish.info/37945453/polish-wikipedia-shuts-down-in-protest-at-eu-copyright-law|dead-url=no|work=Poland in English|publisher=[[Telewizja Polska]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729061112/https://polandinenglish.info/37945453/polish-wikipedia-shuts-down-in-protest-at-eu-copyright-law|archive-date=29 July 2018|access-date=29 July 2018}}</ref> later followed by others including the [[Spanish Wikipedia|Spanish]],<ref name="PagesShutDown" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/tecnologia/redes/abci-wikipedia-espanol-cierra-forma-temporal-protesta-propuesta-copyright-201807041109_noticia.html|title=Wikipedia en español cierra de forma temporal en protesta por la propuesta de copyright de la UE|work=abc|access-date=4 July 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref> [[Estonian Wikipedia|Estonian]], [[Latvian Wikipedia|Latvian]], [[Polish Wikipedia|Polish]],<ref name="PagesShutDown" /><ref name="PolishWikipedia" /> [[French Wikipedia|French]] and [[Portuguese Wikipedia|Portuguese]] ones,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tehnika.postimees.ee/4513784/eesti-vikipeedia-pani-protesti-margiks-oma-lehekulje-kinni|title=Eesti Vikipeedia pani protesti märgiks oma lehekülje kinni|work=Tehnika|access-date=4 July 2018|language=et}}</ref> blacked its pages for readers on 3–5 July, whereas, the English Wikipedia added a banner asking the readers in Europe to contact their representatives in the European Parliament.<ref name="ItalyWikipedia" />

Members of the European Parliament who oppose the changes include [[Julia Reda]], [[Heidi Hautala]], and [[Daniel Dalton (British politician)|Dan Dalton]].<ref name="PM2018">{{cite web |title=MEPs rally against planned EU copyright reform |url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/meps-rally-against-planned-eu-copyright-reform |website=theparliamentmagazine.eu |accessdate=1 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name="PM2018June19">{{cite news |title=Tensions heighten ahead of crunch EU copyright reform vote |url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/tensions-heighten-ahead-crunch-eu-copyright-reform-vote |accessdate=1 July 2018 |work=theparliamentmagazine.eu }}</ref><ref name="PM2018Green" /> Reda describes the efforts behind the law as large media companies trying to force "platforms and search engines to use their snippets and to pay for them".<ref>{{cite web |title=Julia Reda discusses the current Proposal for a Directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market – Kluwer Copyright Blog |url=http://copyrightblog.kluweriplaw.com/2018/06/18/julia-reda-discusses-current-proposal-directive-copyright-digital-single-market/ |website=Kluwer Copyright Blog |accessdate=1 July 2018 |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> Parties that oppose the legislation include the [[European Green Party]] and the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP),<ref name="PM2018Green">{{cite web |title=Legal affairs committee approves controversial EU copyright proposals |url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/legal-affairs-committee-approves-controversial-eu-copyright-proposals |website=theparliamentmagazine.eu |accessdate=1 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=":11">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukip.org/national-ukip-news-item.php?id=18|title=UKIP opposes the EU's Copyright Directive in the Single Digital Market|date=July 3, 2018|website=[[UK Independence Party]]|access-date=November 29, 2018}}</ref> with UKIP leader and MEP, [[Gerard Batten]], saying that the proposed directive may "destroy the capacity for free speech on the internet and social media".<ref name=":11" /> Batten further noted that an international agreement, and not a EU directive, was needed to protect "the legitimate rights of creators, authors and innovators", whilst not stifling "free speech and information dissemination".<ref name=":11" />

=== Academic publishing ===
The proposal is generally supported by academic publishers including the [[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers]].<ref name="Nature2018">{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|date=5 April 2018|title=EU copyright reforms draw fire from scientists|journal=Nature|volume=556|issue=7699|pages=14–15|doi=10.1038/d41586-018-03837-7}}</ref> This group has nevertheless criticised the proposal for excluding scientific publishers from the provisions of Article 11, describing the exclusion as "unwarranted and potentially discriminatory".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stm-assoc.org/2016_09_14_News_Release_STM_response_to_Directive_on_Copyright_in_the_Single_Digital_Market.pdf|title=STM response to Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market|last=|first=|date=2016-09-14|website=|publisher=[[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers|STM]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-08-11}}</ref>

The [[Eurodoc|European Council for Doctoral Candidates and Junior Researchers]] opposes the proposal on the grounds that Article 13's exemption for non-commercial groups does not cover all scientific repositories, and cites the [[Horizon 2020]] project as an example of commercial work in the sector. They also generally agree with the claims of other opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurodoc.net/eurodoc-open-letter-copyright-directive.pdf|title=Eurodoc Open Letter to European Parliament on Copyright Directive|date=2 July 2018|website=[[Eurodoc]]|access-date=2 July 2018}}</ref> The [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]], an [[open access]] advocacy group, opposes the proposal in principle.<ref name="Nature2018" />

=== Case law ===
In 2012, the [[European Court of Justice]] ruled that existing EU law "must be interpreted as precluding a national court from issuing an injunction against a hosting service provider which requires it to install a system for filtering...with a view to preventing works from being made available to the public in breach of copyright", arguing that such an injunction "could potentially undermine freedom of information, since that system might not distinguish adequately between unlawful content and lawful content, with the result that its introduction could lead to the blocking of lawful communications".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?text=&docid=119512doclang=EN&cid=2283803|title=Belgische Vereniging van Auteurs, Componisten en Uitgevers CVBA (SABAM) v Netlog NV|last=|first=|date=16 February 2012|website=[[CURIA]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref>

A similar view can be seen in Case C-160/15 ''GS Media BV v Sanoma Media Netherlands BV, Playboy & Britt Geertruida Dekker'' and in Case C-70/10 ''Scarlet Extended SA v SABAM, BEA Video, BEA Music & ISPA''.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}

=== Human rights ===
The [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] raised concerns that the proposal was incompatible with the 1966 [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]]. In a public letter, special rapporteur, [[David Kaye (law professor)|David Kaye]], argued that the proposal's reluctance to pin down precise obligations on content hosts created "significant legal uncertainty" inconsistent with the covenant's requirement that any restrictions on freedom of expression be "provided by law". He concluded that this could lead to "pressure on content sharing providers to err on the side of caution". Kaye also criticised the lack of "prior judicial review" inherent in the system, and the similarly extrajudicial nature of its appeals process.<ref name="auto8">{{cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Issues/Opinion/Legislation/OL-OTH-41-2018.pdf|title=European Union draft directive on copyright in the digital single market|author=Kaye|first=David|date=13 June 2018|website=|publisher=[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|UNHCHR]]|id=OL OTH 41/2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

The letter also raised concerns regarding the lack of protection for non-profit groups, although such groups had been excluded from the proposal's provisions prior to its publication.<ref name="consilium_europa01" /> The EU was invited to respond within 60{{Nbsp}}days.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}

