The '''Eurovision Song Contest 2012''' was the 57th edition of the annual [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. It took place in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]], following [[Ell&nbsp;&&nbsp;Nikki]]'s win at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011 contest]] in [[Düsseldorf]], [[Germany]] with the song "[[Running Scared (Eldar & Nigar song)|Running Scared]]" — marking the first time that the country had won the contest. The contest was held at the newly constructed [[Baku Crystal Hall]], with semi-finals held on 22 and 24 May 2012, followed by the final held on 26 May 2012. Forty-two countries competed in the contest — one less than the record number of 43 set at [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|the previous contest]], with [[Montenegro in the Eurovision Song Contest|Montenegro]] returning for the first time since [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]], and the withdrawal of [[Armenia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Armenia]] due to security concerns in relation to the ongoing [[Nagorno-Karabakh conflict]] with Azerbaijan, and [[Poland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Poland]] due to financial concerns.

The contest was won by singer [[Loreen (singer)|Loreen]] from [[Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest|Sweden]] with the song "[[Euphoria (Loreen song)|Euphoria]]" — written by [[Thomas G:son]] and [[Peter Boström]], the song scored a total of 372 points. [[Russia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Russia]] finished in second place, with [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Serbia]] finishing in third. They were followed by the host country, [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Azerbaijan]], which reached the 4th place. [[Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Albania]] finished 5th, achieving its first top 5 placing. [[Germany in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Germany]], [[Italy in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Italy]] and [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Spain]] were the three members of the "Big Five" that managed to rank within the top 10, finishing in 8th, 9th and 10th places respectively.

The lead-up to the contest was met with political concerns and protests surrounding the host country, including its [[human rights]] record and allegations by advocacy groups that Baku was carrying out forced [[eviction]]s in the construction of the contest's venue, along with objections to the contest's presence by [[Iran]]ian officials—who felt that the event was anti-Islamic because it was, according to them, a "[[gay pride parade|gay parade]]".

